2.1 Question

Is there any statistical difference between mobile and desktop in term of cpc ?

2.2 Ans

prop.test(
  x = c(nrow(cpc_m_zero), nrow(cpc_d_zero)),
  n = c(nrow(cpc_m), nrow(cpc_d)),
  correct = FALSE
)
## 
##  2-sample test for equality of proportions without continuity correction
## 
## data:  c(nrow(cpc_m_zero), nrow(cpc_d_zero)) out of c(nrow(cpc_m), nrow(cpc_d))
## X-squared = 5.1056, df = 1, p-value = 0.02385
## alternative hypothesis: two.sided
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.003895288 0.054119979
## sample estimates:
##     prop 1     prop 2 
## 0.07175573 0.04274809

The zero-CPC rate is higher on mobile (7.18%) than on desktop (4.27%). With a p-value of 0.02385 (< 0.05), the difference is statistically significant. This indicates that mobile and desktop platforms do not share the same zero-CPC rate.

For better visualization, we applied a log transformation to the conv values. The pre-experiment distribution is wider at higher values (at approximately 14 conversion count), while the conversion count during the experiments reached only 11 unÃ­t, suggesting that less users achieved higher conversion rates before the experiment. The post-experiment values are more evenly spread, with the median slightly lower than in the pre-experiment group, indicating an overall negative shift in conversion performance after the advertising experiment. Additionally, the post-treatment distribution shows slightly higher variability compared to the pre-experiment distribution. more importance, thÃ­s plot suggÃ©t that these samples are not follÆ¡w by the Gaussian distribution In conclusion,these figures indicates the experimental change had a negative impact on the average conversion success but stabilized the performance outcomes.

4.1 Question

applied A/B testing on conversion rate

4.2 Ans

As what announce above, the familliar t-test wont be use directly, Letâs try a data-driven method that i learned 4 weeks ago: Boostrap test on mean.

We state our hypothesis:

\[ \begin{aligned} H_0: \ \mu_{\text{platform A}} &= \mu_{\text{platform B}} \\ H_1: \ \mu_{\text{platform A}} &\neq \mu_{\text{platform B}} \end{aligned} \]

where \(\mu_{\text{platform A}}\) and \(\mu_{\text{platform B}}\) represent the true mean conversion rates of each platform.

set.seed(42)

conv_m <- data_b |> 
  filter(platform == "m") |>
  select(conv) |>
  pull()

conv_d <- data_b |>
  filter(platform == "d") |>
  select(conv) |>
  pull()

observed_diff <- abs(mean(conv_m,na.rm = TRUE) - mean(conv_d,na.rm = TRUE))
cat(sprintf("Sá»± khÃ¡c biá»t Quan sÃ¡t (B - A): %.4f\n\n", observed_diff))
## Sá»± khÃ¡c biá»t Quan sÃ¡t (B - A): 16.1756

VÃ²ng láº·p Bootstrap

n_m <- length(conv_m)
n_d <- length(conv_d)
N_total <- n_m + n_d

num_bootstraps <- 10000
diffs_simulated <- numeric(num_bootstraps)

cat(sprintf("Boostraping (%d times)...\n", num_bootstraps))
## Boostraping (10000 times)...
conv_m_til <- conv_m - mean(conv_m,na.rm = TRUE)
conv_d_til <- conv_d -mean(conv_d,na.rm = TRUE)

conv_sm <- sd(conv_m,na.rm = TRUE)
conv_sd <- sd(conv_d,na.rm = TRUE)


for (i in 1:num_bootstraps) {
  sample_m <- sample(conv_m_til,
                     size = n_m,
                     replace = TRUE)
  
  sample_d <- sample(conv_d_til,
                     size = n_d,
                     replace = TRUE)
  
  
  # TÃ­nh vÃ  lÆ°u láº¡i sá»± khÃ¡c biá»t cá»§a máº«u mÃ´ phá»ng
  diffs_simulated[i] <- (mean(sample_m,na.rm = TRUE) - mean(sample_d,na.rm = TRUE))/sqrt((sd(sample_m,na.rm = TRUE)^2)/n_m + (sd(sample_d,na.rm = TRUE)^2)/n_d )
}

cat("Done.\n\n")
## Done.

TÃ­nh P-Value vÃ  Káº¿t luáº­n â

T_obs <- observed_diff/sqrt((conv_sm^2)/n_m + (conv_sd^2)/n_d )

p_value <- sum(abs(diffs_simulated) >= abs(T_obs)) / num_bootstraps

# In káº¿t quáº£
cat("--- Káº¿t quáº£ Kiá»m tra Bootstrap Shift Method ---\n")
## --- Káº¿t quáº£ Kiá»m tra Bootstrap Shift Method ---
cat(sprintf("Observed Statistic (Y_bar1 - Y_bar2): %.4f\n", T_obs))
## Observed Statistic (Y_bar1 - Y_bar2): 6.6815
cat(sprintf("Bootstrap P-Value (Hai phÃ­a): %.4f\n", p_value))
## Bootstrap P-Value (Hai phÃ­a): 0.0000
# Kiá»m tra P-Value
if (p_value < 0.05) {
  cat("\nKáº¿t luáº­n: P-value < 0.05. BÃ¡c bá» H0. CÃ³ sá»± khÃ¡c biá»t cÃ³ Ã½ nghÄ©a thá»ng kÃª giá»¯a mu1 vÃ  mu2.\n")
} else {
  cat("\nKáº¿t luáº­n: P-value >= 0.05. KhÃ´ng bÃ¡c bá» H0. KhÃ´ng cÃ³ Äá»§ báº±ng chá»©ng vá» sá»± khÃ¡c biá»t.\n")
}
## 
## Káº¿t luáº­n: P-value < 0.05. BÃ¡c bá» H0. CÃ³ sá»± khÃ¡c biá»t cÃ³ Ã½ nghÄ©a thá»ng kÃª giá»¯a mu1 vÃ  mu2.

This violin plot compares conversion performance âpreâ and âpostâ an experiment. Given that conversion (\(\text{conv}\)) drives ROI, the key insight is about performance stability and magnitude.

  • Median Decline: The median \(\text{log1p}(\text{conv})\) dropped from âpreâ (approx. 0.75) to âpostâ (belÆ¡ 0.5). This signifies that the typical, or average, the ROI rates decreased following the change.
  • Increased Volatility (Risk): The âpostâ distribution shows higher variability and a pronounced, thin upper tail. This indicates the change introduced greater performance volatility and a higher concentration of low/zero-conversion events alongside a few extreme high performers.

In conclusion The experiment negatively impacted the consistency and average performance, leading to lower generalized ROI and introducing higher risk (volatility) in the conversion outcomes across the platform(s).

5.1 Question

applied A/B testing on conversion rate

5.2 Ans

As what announce above, the familliar t-test wont be use directly, Letâs try a data-driven method that i learned 4 weeks ago: Boostrap test on mean.

We state our hypothesis:

\[ \begin{aligned} H_0: \ \mu_{\text{ROI A}} &= \mu_{\text{ROI B}} \\ H_1: \ \mu_{\text{ROI A}} &\neq \mu_{\text{ROI B}} \end{aligned} \]

where \(\mu_{\text{ROI A}}\) and \(\mu_{\text{ROI B}}\) represent the true mean conversion rates of each platform.

set.seed(42)

roi_m <- data_b |> 
  filter(platform == "m") |>
  select(roi) |>
  pull()

roi_d <- data_b |>
  filter(platform == "d") |>
  select(roi) |>
  pull()

observed_diff <- abs(mean(roi_m,na.rm = TRUE) - mean(roi_d,na.rm = TRUE))
cat(sprintf("Sá»± khÃ¡c biá»t Quan sÃ¡t (B - A): %.4f\n\n", observed_diff))
## Sá»± khÃ¡c biá»t Quan sÃ¡t (B - A): 0.0126

VÃ²ng láº·p Bootstrap

mean(roi_m,na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 1.369562
n_m <- length(roi_m)
n_d <- length(roi_d)
N_total <- n_m + n_d

num_bootstraps <- 10000
diffs_simulated <- numeric(num_bootstraps)

cat(sprintf("Boostraping (%d times)...\n", num_bootstraps))
## Boostraping (10000 times)...
roi_sm <- sd(roi_m,na.rm = TRUE)
roi_sd <- sd(roi_d,na.rm = TRUE)

roi_m_til <- roi_m - mean(roi_m,na.rm = TRUE)
roi_d_til <- roi_d -mean(roi_d,na.rm = TRUE)




for (i in 1:num_bootstraps) {
  sample_m <- sample(roi_m_til,
                     size = n_m,
                     replace = TRUE)
  
  sample_d <- sample(roi_d_til,
                     size = n_d,
                     replace = TRUE)
  
  
  # TÃ­nh vÃ  lÆ°u láº¡i sá»± khÃ¡c biá»t cá»§a máº«u mÃ´ phá»ng
  diffs_simulated[i] <- (mean(sample_m,na.rm = TRUE) - mean(sample_d,na.rm = TRUE))/sqrt((sd(sample_m,na.rm = TRUE)^2)/n_m + (sd(sample_d,na.rm = TRUE)^2)/n_d )
}

cat("Done.\n\n")
## Done.

TÃ­nh P-Value vÃ  Káº¿t luáº­n â

T_obs <- observed_diff/sqrt((roi_sm^2)/n_m + (roi_sd^2)/n_d )

p_value <- sum(abs(diffs_simulated) >= abs(T_obs)) / num_bootstraps

# In káº¿t quáº£
cat("--- Káº¿t quáº£ Kiá»m tra Bootstrap Shift Method ---\n")
## --- Káº¿t quáº£ Kiá»m tra Bootstrap Shift Method ---
cat(sprintf("Observed Statistic (Y_bar1 - Y_bar2): %.4f\n", T_obs))
## Observed Statistic (Y_bar1 - Y_bar2): 0.1461
cat(sprintf("Bootstrap P-Value (Hai phÃ­a): %.4f\n", p_value))
## Bootstrap P-Value (Hai phÃ­a): 0.8850
# Kiá»m tra P-Value
if (p_value < 0.05) {
  cat("\nKáº¿t luáº­n: P-value < 0.05. BÃ¡c bá» H0. CÃ³ sá»± khÃ¡c biá»t cÃ³ Ã½ nghÄ©a thá»ng kÃª giá»¯a mu1 vÃ  mu2.\n")
